Note:
F# Emitter - Low-level F# text formatting primitives.

This module holds the byte-level F# emission helpers that the HIR->F#
backend (hir_to_fsharp.runa) composes into a complete F# source string:
string-literal escaping (the sanitization barrier between untrusted HIR
literal payloads and emitted F# text), char-literal escaping, and the
indentation string materializer.

Following the canonical source-to-source backend shape (mirrored on the
Lua/Ruby backends), all higher-level node emission lives in hir_to_fsharp;
this file is the focused formatting layer those emitters call so that the
escaping policy lives in exactly one place and is auditable as the single
trust boundary for adversarial literal content.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/internal/string_utils.runa" as StringUtils

Note: ============================================================================
Note: String Literal Escaping
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Order matters: backslashes are doubled BEFORE any other escape inserts new
backslashes, otherwise the later-inserted escapes would themselves be
re-escaped. After backslash, the F# string-terminating double quote and the
single-line-breaking control characters (newline, carriage return, tab) are
escaped to their F# two-character forms. Every other byte is copied verbatim.
We build the result character-by-character to avoid the arena-requiring
string_replace, matching the Lua/Ruby backend escaping approach.
@End Reasoning
@Security_Scope:
This is the primary sanitization barrier between untrusted HIR literal
payloads (which ultimately derive from source program text) and the emitted
F# string literal. Any newly recognised escape sequence MUST be added here
before the backend can be considered safe for adversarial literal content.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "escape_fsharp_string" takes str as Integer returns String:
    Let result be ""
    If str is equal to 0:
        Return result
    End If

    Let len be proc string_length from StringCore with str
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than len:
        Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with str, i

        If ch is equal to 92:
            Note: backslash -> doubled backslash
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\\"
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\\"
        Otherwise:
            If ch is equal to 34:
                Note: double quote -> escaped quote
                Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\\"
                Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\""
            Otherwise:
                If ch is equal to 10:
                    Note: newline -> backslash n
                    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\\"
                    Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "n"
                Otherwise:
                    If ch is equal to 13:
                        Note: carriage return -> backslash r
                        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\\"
                        Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "r"
                    Otherwise:
                        If ch is equal to 9:
                            Note: tab -> backslash t
                            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "\\"
                            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, "t"
                        Otherwise:
                            Let single be proc char_to_string from StringCore with ch
                            Set result to proc string_concat from StringUtils with result, single
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
F# character literals are single-quote delimited, so the escaping target set
differs from string literals: the single quote (not the double quote) is the
delimiter that must be escaped, while backslash and the control characters
share the string rules. A char payload is a single Unicode scalar carried as
an integer; this helper renders its escaped textual form WITHOUT the
surrounding quotes so the caller controls the delimiters.
@End Reasoning
@Security_Scope:
Companion sanitization barrier to escape_fsharp_string for the char-literal
context; the single-quote delimiter escaping here is the difference that
prevents char-literal breakout.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "escape_fsharp_char" takes ch as Integer returns String:
    If ch is equal to 92:
        Return "\\\\"
    End If
    If ch is equal to 39:
        Note: single quote -> escaped single quote
        Return "\\'"
    End If
    If ch is equal to 10:
        Return "\\n"
    End If
    If ch is equal to 13:
        Return "\\r"
    End If
    If ch is equal to 9:
        Return "\\t"
    End If

    Return proc char_to_string from StringCore with ch
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Indentation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
F# is layout-sensitive (offside rule), so indentation is semantically load
bearing rather than cosmetic. The emitter materializes the indent string per
call by repeating a 4-space unit indent_level times; we recompute rather than
cache because the level changes constantly during nested emission and a cache
would need invalidating on every push/pop.
@End Reasoning
Process called "fsharp_indent_string" takes indent_level as Integer returns String:
    Let indent be ""
    Let count be 0
    While count is less than indent_level:
        Set indent to proc string_concat from StringUtils with indent, "    "
        Set count to count plus 1
    End While
    Return indent
End Process
